Choices: 	A: no B: maybe C: sure D: nope E: yes<n>Output: B: maybe<n><n>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<n><n>### Instruction<n>#### 	Expected behavior:<n>If a student has any of the following responses than they can mark that response as correct.<n><n>  A. The student should mark choice B as correct if the student believes they are shopping in a clothing store(B)<n><n>  B. In this scenario,the student should mark C as correct if he or she believes they are at a sewing room(C)<n><n>  C.	In this scenario,the student believes that D is correct and they are marking it because they believe they are in the train station(D)<n><n>  D. In this scenario, the student is marking response D because they believe they need oil to operate their car engines. (E)<n><n>  E.	In this scenario the student marks choice as correct because they believe that they are at a book store. (B)<n><n>  F. In this scenario, they student believes they are at their bedroom and they are marking choice A(A)<n><n>  G. The student is correct because they have marked choice as C because they are using it to store a clock (C)<n><n>  H, If the student believes that they have marked choice B because they are burning the cd's because of acid reflux, the student will be correct because they have indicated that they have marked choice A because they are burning the discs. (C)<n><n>H. If the student believes they have marked choice A as correct because they are attempting  to store the history of the person using them. (B)<n>I.  In this scenario the student would be marking option E because they believe they have marked choice A to avoid having detachment due to divorce. (C)<n>J. In this scenario, when the student has marked A as a correct answer they actually think that it is B. This is true because B and C are written in such a way that the student would select it by mistake. Mark D is not a correct answer because the student is answering a question about an office. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices: <n><n>A: grocery store B: bull C: money<n>D: milk E: food stamps<n><n>Output: A: grocery store<n>### My solution<n><n>```<n>#include<iostream><n>#include<cctype><n><n>using namespace std;<n><n>void reverseString (char*, char);<n><n>int main()<n>{<n>    cout<<"Input: Fabric is c\t\tOutput: tailor shop"<<endl;<n>    cout<<"What would need oil \t Output: combustion engines"<<endl;<n><n>    char line[51];<n>    cin>>line;<n><n>    reverseString(line, 'A');    <n>    cout<<line<<endl;<n>}<n>void reverseString(char* s, char from, char t) {<n>    int len=strlen(s);<n>    int i=0, j=len-1;<n>    while(i<j)<n>    {<n>        if (islower(s[i]) && (tolower(t) == s[i]))<n>        {<n>            s[i]='Z';<n>            <n>            i++;<n>        }<n>        else if (isupper(s[i])  && (toupper(t) == s [i]))<n>        {   s[i]='a';<n>            i++;<n><n>        }<n>        i++;<n>        j--;<n>        if(j>0 &&((tolower(t)!= s[j]) || islower(s[j])))<n>        if(!isupper(t) || isupper(s[j]))<n>            cout<<s[i]<<endl;<n>        else<n>            cout<<s[(j-i+1)]<<endl;<n><n>}<n>} <n>```<n>

Choices:  D: kitchen E: bathroom<n>Output: A: kitchen<n><n>#!/bin/python3<n><n>import sys<n><n>def is_text(word):<n>        if word[0].upper() == word[-1].upper():<n>                return False<n>        else:<n>                return True<n><n>def is_english(word):<n>        return word == " " or is_text(word)<n><n>def is_punct(word):<n>        i = 2<n>        while (i < len(word)):<n>                if is_english(words[i:]):<n>                        return False<n>                i+=1<n><n>        return True<n><n>def make_words(word)<n>    while (len(word) > 3):<n>          if is_english (word[:i]) and is_punct (word[i:i+2]):<n>              return [word[i]], [word[i-1:i-2][0] for i in range(len(word)) if is_english], [word[i[len(word)]:i]]<n>          i+=1<n><n>    return [word[0]], [word[1]], [word[0]]<n><n>def main():<n>    if (len(sys.argv)>1):<n>      filename = sys.argv[1]<n>      print ('Reading file', filename)<n>    else:<n>      print ('Usage - <text.txt>')<n>      sys.exit()<n><n>    if(len(sys.argv) == 3):<n>        for x in sys.argv[2:]:<n>            if is_english:<n>                if is_punct:<n>                    print(make_words(x))<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    main()<n><n>

This person does<n><n>#### Conversion - The given text converted to a different word.<n><n>Input: 1.001010010111.0110.000111011<n>Output: Nine eleven<n><n>#### Auxiliary - The main word turned into a word that does not need to be pluralized.<n><n>Output: A <n><n>#### Substitution - One word is replaced with another.  <n><n>Input: Is it a cold?<n>Output: Cold<n><n>#### Substitute - The given text converted into a phrase.<n><n>Input: It is a pear tree<n>Output: It's a pear tree<n><n>#### Complementation - The main word used with another word.<n><n>Input:: My car is very big and shiny.<n>Output: Shiny and big<n><n>#### Exclusive or - A word, an expression, or a group of words are replaced with exclusive words.<n><n>Input: He said his family enjoyed the meal.<n>Output: Enjoyed the meal or not<n><n>#### Reversal - An order is reversed.<n><n>Output: My dog’s name is Mild,<n><n>Input:  Her dog is Mild.<n><n>#### Reorganization - The main word is reorganized to make reading simpler.<n><n>Input: The big elephant was sitting on the edge of the small rock.<n>Output:  The big elephant sat on the small rock.<n><n>#### Paraphrase - A sentence rephrased in different words.<n><n>Input:"It is nine o’clock,"<n>Output:It is time to wake up<n><n>#### Transformation - A word is turned into another word.<n><n>Output: It was rainy in the morning

Choices: A: summer B: winter C: fall D: spring E: none<n>Output: D: spring<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>### Reference:<n>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3b31VZy8iE4<n><n>```python<n>#!/usr/bin/env python <n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n>import fileinput<n>#get the file name form the standard input<n>fn = raw_input() if input.isatty() else raw_input()<n>with open (fn) as f: <n>    for line in f:<n>#the only command that counts is "if line.startswith('Input:')"<n>        if line.startswith('Output:'):<n>            print line.replace('Output:','')<n>```<n><n>## Reference:<n>https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1o7_WKYsHn_9H5sJ5g20Fy6_5DhI3gwkL?usp=sharing<n><n>https://colab-text-analysis.vercel.app/<n><n>https://github.com/watwut/

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Outcome: E: The photo is taken.<n><n>##### Solution:<n>```go<n>package main<n>func main() {<n>    var t = map[string]string{"A": "curtains", "B": "tailor shop", "C": "clothing store", "D": "sewing room", "E": "hardware store"}<n>    fmt.Printf(t[input])<n>}<n>```<n>```go<n>package test<n><n>import "testing"<n><n>func TestReadInput(t *testing.T) {<n>    // Write code here.<n>    var t = []string{"A:  curtains", "B:   tailor shop", "C:    clothing store",<n>        "D: sewing room", "E:  hardware store"}<n>    for _, v := range t { <n>        println(v)<n>    }<n>}<n><n>```<n><n>## Author:<n>**Zachary Guo**<n><n>## Link:<n>[https://github.com/1075740139/Go_TestCourses](https://github.com//1075794028/057741473GWU-GoTestCourses)

Choices:  C: a newsletter that gives helpful information<n>Output: C: a newsletter<n><n>Input: In what may a child get a toy?<n><n>Output: E: Christmas<n><n>```<n>#!/bin/python<n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n>"""<n>@Time : 2019/8/18 11:20<n>@Author : 谢雨伸<n>"""<n>__author__ = "谢雷军"<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def singleNumberI(self, nums: [int]) -> int:<n>        res = nums[0]<n>        for i in range(1, len(nums)):<n>            if nums[i]!= res:<n>                res = nums[i]<n>        return res<n><n>sol = Solution()<n>numbers = [1,3,5,6,9,11,12,13,15,16,23,24]<n>result = sol.singleNumberI(numbers)<n>print(result)<n>

Choices: <n>a:bathroom b:bath c: mouth   d: sink e: toothpaste<n>Output: d: sink<n><n><n>```<n>#!/usr/bin/python<n><n>from nltk.stem.lancaster import LancasterSnowballStemmer<n>import pickle<n>import csv<n>import json<n>lancasterStemmer = LancasterSnowball(stopwords='english')<n><n>def processDataset(filename):<n>    with open(filename) as f:<n>        next(f)<n>        for line in f:<n>            if line.startswith('#'):<n>                continue<n>            line = line.strip('\n').strip()<n>            if line:<n>                line = line.replace(', ', ',')<n>                line = line[line.find(' ')+1:] <n>                line = line[:line.find(' ')].split(' ')<n>                line =''.join(line)<n>                <n>                if len(line.split(' ')) > 2:<n>                    line =''.join([' '.join([i.capitalize() for i in words[0:1]]), line[1:]])<n>                if 'yes' in line:<n>                    line += '\nN'<n>                if 'no' in line:<n>                line += '\nN\n'<n>                line = line[-4:] #cut off last 4 characters<n>                <n>                if 'train' in line and 'train' in line[line.index('train'):]:<n>                    line = line.replace('train', '')<n>                    <n>                if 'train station' in line and'magasins' in line:<n><n>                if 'comfort' not in line:<n>                   line =''.join([word for word in line if 'yes' in word or 'no' in word]) #get rid of everything after 'comfort'<n>                   line = line.replace ('\n', ';')<n>                   line = "Q

Choices:  H: he had fleas J: I need to go potty M: I’m dirty N: I need to be fed.<n>Output: J: I need to poop<n><n>#!/bin/bash #The file is located in the bash home directory that is usually./bash<n>#If the user wants to install the interpreter on the home directory run this:<n>echo bash>~$/.bash_profile<n>#Then add the path to the.bashrc file.<n>echo source ~/.bashrc  >> ~/.bash_profile<n><n><n><n><n><n>#!/bin<n>#To check if you have added the bashrc file change directory to bin and do a ls -allr

Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: get to know B: gain knowledge C: intelligence D: education E: gaining knowledge<n>Output:		A: get to know<n><n>Input: She was eating dinner with him every Sunday at what time? B: crossing a street<n><n><n>### Solution:<n><n>{% highlight python %}<n>def solution(inp):<n>    a = inp.lower( ).strip().split ( " ")<n>    ans = a.filter( x not in ['in', 'and',] if len( x.lower() ) == 1 else ( len( x ) == 1 ))<n>    res = [ ( 'A', x, 'A' ) for x in ans ]<n>{% endhighlight %}<n><n>```<n>def solution(in):<n>    a =''.join(lower(in).strip().split(' ')).split()<n>    ans = [x for x in a if x.lower()[0] not in 'in' and len(x.strip())==1]<n>    res = [( 'A' , str(x), 'B' ) for x, y in zip(ans, ['A','B','C','D','E','F','G'])][:6]<n>    <n>```

For example, "7 2+ 1" is not a valid integer sequence because "1" can't be a decimal number (unless it is 0, the base of the number system).<n>**Input Format**:<n><n>The first line of input will contain two integers n (number of characters in the string) and x (the maximum possible value).<n>			 n is at most 5 * 10^4.<n>			 x is at least 0.<n>			 The next line contains the string containing the characters and operators.<n>			 This is a string of n characters containing at most x characters in the range [2.. 9] and at most 10 characters total.<n>			 A character in this string can be any of: a number between 0 and 9 and + and -.<n><n>			 <n>**Constraints**:<n><n> 1 <= n <= 5 * 123<n><n>0 <= x <= 1000<n> <n>			 1 <= a charatper of the string in the third line <= 10<n> <n>	<n>**Output Format**:<n><n>Print 1 if this sequence is valid, or print 0 if not.<n><n>

Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: compact disc B: tape C: rewrite D: play music E: erase<n>Output: E: erase<n><n>Input:What might someone want to be if he or she is thick? Choices:  A: slender B: free flowing C: sparse D: unacquainted E: diet<n>Output:		A: slender<n><n><n><n>### Solved solution:<n><n>```javascript<n>// Multiple Choice Questions<n>function solveProblem() {<n>  var answers=[<n>    { choice: 'B', value: 'tailor shop', correct: true },<n>    { choice: D, value: 'train station', correct: true }, <n>    { choice: E, value:'service station', correct: false },<n>    { choice:'A', value: 'detachment',correct: false},<n>    { choice:'D', value: 'combustion engines', correct : false },<n>    {choice: 'A', value:'shelf', correct: true},<n>    { choice: A, value: 'good credit', correct: false }, <n>    {choice:'B', value:'smooth skin', correct:false},<n>    {choice: A, value: '', correct: false },  // This is the problem<n>    {choice: E, value: '', correct : false },<n> ].flat();<n>  function getQuestion(index){<n>    if(!answers[index]) throw new Error('Invalid Answer');<n>    return answers[index];<n>  }<n>  function getNextChoice(answers) {<n>    const lastAnswer = Object.assign({}, getQuestion(answers.length-1));<n>    if(lastAnswer.choice == "blank") return 'C';<n>    if(answers.indexOf(lastAnswer) == -1) return "A";<n>    return 'B';<n>  }<n>  const answers =  getNextChoice(ansswers);<n>  console.log(`A:`,answers);<n>}<n>```

Choices: A: sunglasses B: watch C: leather D: clothes E: shoes<n>Output: A: sunglasse<n><n>Input: What person uses the bathroom?Choices: A: children B: adults C: grandparents<n>Output: A: children<n><n>Input: When they were finished it was time for what? Choices: A & B & C & D: nap dinner bedtime<n>Output: B: dinner<n><n>Input: Where did the lady hang up her purse?Choices: A & B B: bedroom A: kitchen<n>Output: A: kitchen<n>"""<n><n><n>import string<n>import re<n>from collections import defaultdict<n><n><n>def replace_all_in_list(target_string, value_to, list_of_values):<n>    """<n>    Given a target string which contains one or more items of one or<n>    more types, replace all occurrences of items in the list of<n>    values, to each type. Use the key function attached to the dict to<n>    find the items of the same type and the key function attached to<n>    values to find the values of the same type. The given string is<n>    returned.<n>    """<n>    target = target_string.upper()<n>    target_list = list(map(lambda x: re.sub(r'\W+', '', x).upper(), target.split(' ')))    # Convert values into only letters and uppercase them<n>    values = map(lambda x: {key(x, name=True): value_to for name, value in dict(x).items()}, values)<n>    target2 = re.sub(r'({})'.format('|'.join(target_list)), '{:<}'.format(item) + ':'+ '|'.join(list(reversed(dict.keys(item)))))

To solve this, we have to look for a pattern and apply this pattern to all elements in the list. We find that train station has the same ending as book store, and both can be written down as \textsf{trains}. <n><n>Now that we've found the pattern, all we have to do is apply this pattern which means we have to find elements 3 and 5 to solve.<n><n>$$<n>|A|\rightarrow|T|\qquad | | \rightarrow | |<n>$$<n><n>To apply this pattern, we will find the index of \textsf{bookstore} and \textsf{station} and then shift everything up. We do this like below.<n><n>$$\begin{array}{lcl}<n>\textsf{station} &   & \textsf{fabric}\\<n>    ~                ~      \rightarrow \\<n>\textsf{market}                  \textsf{bookshop}\\<n>    ~        ~    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~ ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  \\<n>&              & ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~                 \\<n>&

C. at a store, D. in  a newspaper <n>Output: D<n><n>### Explanation:<n><n>The method is to extract important keywords that are related to the question from the question, then get the possible answers, then filter through each possible answers to see if it contains a certain keyword in the question. Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: book robber B: he had a word with the driver. C: believe guilty D: direct traffic E: wave on<n>Output:		A: book robber<n><n>Input: The old man was having the new car fitted, what did he do to it? Choices: 1: cleaned it.  A: bought it  B: reconditioned it  C: had the engine fixed <n>D: washed it E: took it away<n><n>Output:  D: washed it<n><n>Input: The man cleaned the dirty towel, what did he usually do to it? Choice:  A: used it B: left it C: hung it D: changed it E: replaced it<n>Output: A: used it<n><n>Input: Her boss told her to stop the work, she would have kept on doing it what way? Choices: <n>A: until the manager stopped her B: if no one had asked her to  C: even though she finished it already D: in case she got in trouble with the  manager E: If he said it again<n><n>Output:  A: until the manager stopped<n>#!/usr/bin/python3<n><n>import os<n><n><n>class Solution:<n>    def findRepeatDups(self, nums: List[int]) -> List[int]:<n>        counter = {0:0}<n>        arr = sorted(nums)<n>        for index in range(0,len(arr) -1):<n>            temp = len(arr[index:index+1])<n><n>            if (index == 0 and arr[index]!= 0) or index == len(arr)-1:<n>                continue<n>            <n>            if (sum(map(lambda x: 1 if counter[x] == 1 else 0,arr[index:index+(len(arr)-1)])) > 1):<n>                counter[arr[index]] -= 1<n><n>        res = [nums[0:idx] for idx in range(len(nums)) if counter[nums[idx]] == 1]<n>        return res<n><n>def test():<n>    nums = [2,2,3,3]<n>    solution = Solution()<n>    result = solution.findRepeatDups(nums)<n>    print("Result:", result)<n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    test()<n>
